message: The legend has no historical support and highly questionable.
Reference removed as direct link of book is not available, thus creating an issue related to verifiability
Reference was a dead link, so it was removed.
He was from Sansi Gotra of Jats.
It seems unnecessary to mention different type of unverifiable claims

There is no mention in any record of jadoun rulers having vast areas as mentioned in this gazetteer. A 19th century Gazetter can not be real substitute of 12th century events. Large number of literature exists of Gaurid era, none of it mentions Jadoun Empire. So legends can not be promoted under history section.

Undid revision 958360394 by [[Special:Contributions/Alivardi|Alivardi]] ([[User talk:Alivardi|talk]]) User Alivardi is consistently damaging Jat related pages in obsessive manner for his vested agenda by giving vague explanations.
There is dispute if she was real daughter of king.

Origin is made brief as it is based on gazetteer source of late 19th century and all other sources are derived from same source. There is not much mention of powerful jadoun clan in contemporary sources of Gaurid invasion.

Since there was no Karoli state back then it is hypothetical that Balchandra was a prince. He is just a name(real or mythical) in genealogy, his connection with karoli is doubtful and based on a legend based on a Gazetter which belongs to late 19th century.
Karauli state was no there before time of Akbar. So there is no question of a prince from Karoli state
Fairly good reason of edit is being given. There was no Karauli state back then in 12th century during Gaurid attack. At that time Kshatriya identity existed, not rajput identity.

According to Wikipedia articles, there was no established rajput identity in 12th centuries. So wikipedia is self contradicting itself. Moreover, there is no contemporary evidence of 12th century existing that Balchand was a Rajput.
